As the average global temperature increases due to human-caused global warming, the ratio between warm temperature and cold temperature records in the U.S. is increasingly skewed toward heat milestones, an Associated Press analysis shows.
The fact that extreme cold records are getting more rare is one of the trends that's becoming clear to people.
Background: AP shared an analysis of warm temperature records versus cold records since 1920 within the Lower 48 states.
The data consists of daily high maximum temperature records as well as daily low minimum temperature records set at a subset of 424 stations from the U.S.
AP reports: "Since 1999, the ratio has been two warm records set or broken for every cold one.